==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*witan'', from Indo-European ''*weid-, *wid-'' ‘see, know’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[wit]], Old Saxon [[wit]] (Ditch [[weet]]), Old High German [[wizzi]] (German [[Witz]]), Old Norse [[vit]] (Swedish [[vett]]).  Compare [[witan#Old English|witan]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/wɪt:/}}

===Noun===
'''witt''' ''n'' (plural same)
# [[mind]], [[understanding]], [[sense]], [[sanity]]

